accessibility.text: Presenter notes 	Okay, so here we are going to have four plots extracted from these four sliced of the models parameter space. 	The first (build) shows you how the sensitive the observer is to changes in position, as a function of spacing. This slice holds first order motion to zero so it is isolating position-defined motion. When spacing is wide, a relatively small change in the position-defined motion leads to a large change in the appearance. When smacking is smaller, position-defined motion has less of an effect. The background here is illustrating the model predictions, while the colors inside the circles are the averages of how the observer responded for these stimuli. 	The second graph (build) holds spacing constant at a narrow value, and shows you how position-defined motion and first-order motion trade off.  You can see that on his scale you are more sensitive to first-order motion (vertical).
The next graph (build) does the same thing but at a wider spacing; here position-defined motion affects the responses more and first-order motion affects the responses less.

The final graph (build) holds position-defined motion closer to zero, that is it is showing you purely the response to first-order motion. At wider spacings, a little bit of first-order motion (starting from zero) turns blue; that is you respond counterclockwise to clockwise first-order motion. That is the repulsion effect I mentioned. As you get to narrower spacings, that negative bias matters less because more elements are being added in.
